# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: candy-apple
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:candy-apple/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:candy-apple/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:candy-apple/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:candy-apple/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:candy-apple/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:candy-apple/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:candy-apple/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:candy-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:candy-apple/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:candy-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:candy-apple/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:candy-apple/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:candy-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:candy-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:candy-apple/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:candy-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:candy-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:candy-apple/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:candy-apple/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:candy-apple/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:candy-apple/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:candy-apple/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:candy-apple/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:candy-apple/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:candy-apple/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:candy-apple/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:candy-apple/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:candy-apple/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:candy-apple/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:candy-apple/allington-pippin] '**Allington Pippin'** is an English cultivar of domesticated apple, with a strong flavour that includes hints of pineapple.
[src:candy-apple/allington-pippin] The Allington Pippin was developed prior to year 1884 by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire, England through a cross breeding of Cox's Orange Pippin and the King of the Pippins.
[src:candy-apple/allington-pippin] This name was not given until 1894, when George Bunyard named it after the village of Allington near Maidstone in Kent, where one of the Bunyard's nurseries was situated.
[src:candy-apple/allington-pippin] This apple is conical shaped and its outer skin is combined from flashy colours of red and orange, flushed and striped, with some russeting.
[src:candy-apple/allington-pippin] Its special mellowing to sharp fruit candy or pineapple flavour is appreciated in multipurpose use: cooking, fresh eating and flavourful apple cider.
[src:candy-apple/allington-pippin] Allington is rather a strong fruit, it has a good storage record of three months or more, and keeps shape in cooking.
[src:candy-apple/allington-pippin] 'Allington Pippin' has a biennial bearing tendency, flowers are partially self-sterile, mid season; harvest period is late.
[src:candy-apple/allington-pippin] The tree is average on general tendency to diseases, but blossom is susceptible to frost.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Allura Red AC was originally created by the Allied Chemical Corporation in 1971.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] In the European Union, it is approved, but it must carry a warning label.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] The US Food and Drug Administration considers it safe for use in food, drugs, and cosmetics.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] It has faced increasing pressure for removal from food in some areas, with California banning it in public schools.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Allura Red AC is manufactured by azo coupling between diazotized cresidinesulfonic acid and 2-naphthol-6-sulfonic acid.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Allura Red AC is a popular dye used worldwide.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Annual production in 1980 was greater than 2.3 million kilograms.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] It was introduced as a replacement for amaranth in the United States.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] The European Union approved Allura Red AC as a food colorant in 1994, but EU countries' local laws banning food colorants were preserved until subsequent changes in the 2000s.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] In the United States, Allura Red AC (also known as FD&C Red #40) is approved by the FDA for use in cosmetics, drugs, and food.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] When prepared as a lake pigment, it is disclosed as Red 40 Lake or Red 40 Aluminum Lake.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] It is used in some tattoo inks and is used in many products, such as cotton candy, soft drinks, candy, cherry-flavored products, children's medications, and dairy products.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] It is occasionally used to dye medicinal tablets to help with identification, such as with fexofenadine, an antihistamine.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] It is by far the most commonly used red dye in the United States, completely replacing amaranth (Red 2) and also replacing erythrosine (Red 3) in most applications due to the negative health effects of those two dyes.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Allura Red AC was developed in 1971 by the Allied Chemical Corporation as a replacement for amaranth, which the FDA banned for carcinogenicity in 1976.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Allura Red AC also allowed for cheaper and faster production and lasted longer in food products.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Since the 2000s, Allura Red AC is the most commonly used red dye. despite potential health concerns.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Throughout its history, it has consistently been used in sweets such as candies and jellies.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Allura Red has been heavily studied by food safety groups in North America and Europe, and remains in wide use.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] However, chronic exposure to the dye has been shown to increase susceptibility to bowel disorders in mice.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] The dye has also been shown to damage the DNA of and cause colonic inflammation in mice.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] The UK's Food Standards Agency commissioned a study of six food dyes, dubbed the "Southampton 6" (tartrazine, Allura Red, Ponceau 4R, Quinoline Yellow, sunset yellow, carmoisine), and sodium benzoate (a preservative) on children in the general population, who consumed them in beverages.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] However, in 2009, the EFSA re-evaluated the data at hand and determined that "the available scientific evidence does not substantiate a link between the color additives and behavioral effects", and in 2014, after further review of the data, the EFSA restored the prior ADI levels.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] In 2015, the EFSA found that the exposure estimates did not exceed the ADI of 7 mg/kg per day in any population.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] However, the EU now requires that all products containing synthetic food dyes display a label reading "may have an adverse effect on activity and attention in children".
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] In contrast, the US GRAS policy does not include color additives and must be dealt with separately.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] The US FDA did not make changes following the publication of the Southampton study.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Following a citizen petition filed by the Center for Science in the Public Interest in 2008, requesting the FDA ban several food additives, the FDA commenced a review of the available evidence but found no evidence to justify changes.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Allura Red AC has previously been banned in Denmark, Belgium, France, Germany, Austria, Switzerland, and Sweden.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] This changed in 2008, when the EU adopted a common framework for authorizing food additives, under which Allura Red AC is not currently banned.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] In Norway and Iceland, it was banned between 1978 and 2001, a period in which azo dyes were only legally used in alcoholic beverages and some fish products.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] In September 2024, California banned the inclusion of Allura Red AC, along with five other artificial dyes, in food served in the state's public schools.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] In April 2025, the US FDA officially announced a plan to phase out Allura Red AC along with other petroleum-based dyes by the end of the year as part of the administration and Health and Human Services Secretary Robert F.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Kennedy Jr.'s Make America Healthy Again initiative.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] The plan does not ban the chemical, relying on food producers working with the FDA to voluntarily remove Allura Red AC from their products.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] The FDA has compiled a spreadsheet of companies who have pledged to remove petroleum based dyes from their products.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] Natural alternatives for red 40 include beet juice/powder, paprika, hibiscus, and red radish.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] The FDA is revoking authorization for the use of FD&C Red No.
[src:candy-apple/allura-red-ac] The FDA keeps a database containing the regulatory status of color additives.
[src:candy-apple/candy-apple] Toffee apples were originally sold in London in the 1890s.
[src:candy-apple/candy-apple] However, according to one source, American William W.
[src:candy-apple/candy-apple] Toffee apples are made by coating an apple with a layer of sugar that has been heated to hard crack stage.
[src:candy-apple/candy-apple] The most common sugar coating is made from sugar (white or brown), corn syrup, water, cinnamon and red food coloring.
[src:candy-apple/candy-apple] Humid weather can prevent the sugar from hardening.
